originalText.text:
Recap of the most divine facial I had recently Naturopathica in Chelsea!
I had the Defy Facial with Karen, a goddess with the most magical hands.
I came in irritated and puffy. I left lifted, toned and positively glowing.

From the moment I stepped into the facility I was set at the ease, what a sanctuary!

The boutique in the entrance of the spa is pristine and I could have spent hours exploring its shelves filled with luxurious creams, potions and self-care but I was guided to something I needed more: quiet.
I was presently surprised to find a changing room with a locker, slippers and a robe I could change into and a shower, if I needed it before or after my treatment.
After changing I went into the dark and very quiet “meditation room” where there were cushions and singing bowls.
I was so impressed by how utterly silent it was, I  happily drifted in and out of thought until my practitioner came to take me away.
Karen, the esthetician I had for my facial, was lovely. Her energy was nurturing and calm, and her assessment of my skin was expert. Exactly what I would expect from a luxury spa.

Karen customized my facial for my visible needs, reduction in fluid & irritation through massage, refining exfoliation and hydration infusion.

Her hands, though, are what will bring me back.
There are plenty of hi- tech gadgets, tools and modalities now that deliver exceptional results.

It’s the human touch, however, that is healing.
Karen and Naturopathica understand that.
The Defy facial is a beautiful marriage of both tech and touch.
Thank you!
Celene L.

originalText.text:
Massage by Kimberly was wonderful! Wish I could give my visit 5 stars.This used to be my go to spot pre pandemic. The reason I commuted from Williamsburg was to be able to sit in the “meditation” room undisturbed. I longed to sit in the room with essential oils and just stare at a wall of moving leaves , as I did prior. It was what I most needed on my day off with a 3 year old at home.

Went today and it was completely different. Nothing on the projector, no essential oils. And was told I couldn’t close the door because other guests need to come in. What? That was never a thing. Guests would open the door and come in quietly.

Was specifically asked “if there was a reason why the door was closed” Umm isn’t it common sense? It’s not much of a meditation room if the door is open with the hallway light coming in and you can hear every single sound that comes from the hallway. Unfortunately that was the selling point for me to continue going. Will no longer be returning.
